Put a large #saucepan of water with a pinch of @salt{pinch} on to boil for the pasta. Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into roughly ½cm pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a garlic press). Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{½}(roughly chopped) (stalks and all). Grate the @parmesan cheese{}.

Put a splash of @olive oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Slit the @Tuscan pork sausage{250%g} skin, remove the meat and add to the pan (discard the skin). Use a #wooden spoon{} to break it up and fry until the edges start to crisp, ~{5%minutes}.

Add the onion and cook until softened, ~{5%minutes}. Stir occasionally. Add the garlic and @fennel seeds{½%tsp} and cook until fragrant, ~{2%minutes}.

> TIP: Fennel is quite a strong flavour. If you're not a massive fan, only use a little to start with.

Add the @tomato puree{30%g} and cook for a further ~{2%minutes}.

Add the @chopped tomatoes{1%400g can} to your pan and allow the ragu to simmer gently until reduced and thickened, ~{12-15%minutes}. Season with a pinch of salt and a grind of @black pepper{grind}.

> TIP: Add a sprinkle of sugar too (if you have some). It will really lift the flavour of the tomatoes.

While your ragu is cooking, add the @pappardelle{200%g} to the boiling water and cook until 'al dente', ~{7%minutes}.

> TIP: 'Al dente' simply means the pasta is cooked through but has a tiny bit of firmness left in the middle. Taste it as you go to get it just right.

Once cooked, drain the pasta in a #colander{} and drizzle over a little @olive oil{} to stop it sticking together. Add the pasta to your ragu along with half of the parsley. Serve on plates and top with the remaining parsley and the parmesan cheese. Buon appetito!